.TH BTRFS\-ASSEMBLE 1 "April 2026" "btrfs-dump @PROJECT_VERSION@" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
btrfs\-assemble \- reassemble a btrfs filesystem image from text
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B btrfs\-assemble
.I input.txt
.I output.img
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B btrfs\-assemble
reads a text representation of btrfs metadata (as produced by
.BR btrfs\-dump (1))
and creates a binary filesystem image.
.PP
Node checksums are computed automatically. The chunk map is built
incrementally from bootstrap entries and CHUNK_ITEM items to resolve
logical addresses to physical offsets.
.PP
The resulting image contains only metadata, file data extents are not
populated. Inline extent data is zero-filled.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print usage information and exit.
.SH INPUT FORMAT
The input is the line-oriented text format produced by
.BR btrfs\-dump (1).
The parser is single-pass and processes the following line types:
.SS Labels
Lines ending with a colon (e.g.\&
.BR CHUNK: ,
.BR ROOT: ,
.BR "Tree 100 (log):" )
are treated as tree labels and skipped.
.SS Superblock
.nf
superblock \fIfield\fR=\fIvalue\fR ... (dev_item \fIfield\fR=\fIvalue\fR ...) \fIfield\fR=\fIvalue\fR ...
.fi
.SS Bootstrap entries
.nf
bootstrap \fIobjectid\fR,CHUNK_ITEM,\fIoffset\fR
chunk_item \fIfield\fR=\fIvalue\fR ...
.fi
.SS Backup roots
.nf
backup \fIfield\fR=\fIvalue\fR ...
.fi
.SS Tree nodes
.nf
header bytenr=\fIX\fR flags=\fIX\fR generation=\fIX\fR owner=\fIX\fR level=\fIX\fR ...
\fIobjectid\fR,\fItype\fR,\fIoffset\fR
\fIitem_type\fR \fIfield\fR=\fIvalue\fR ...
.fi
.PP
For internal nodes (level > 0), key lines include
.B blockptr
and
.B generation
fields.
.SS Escaping
Names and data values use backslash escaping:
.B \e\e
for backslash,
.B \e\0
for space,
.B \er
for carriage return,
.B \en
for newline, and
.B \exXX
for other non-printable characters.
.SS Trailing data
The
.BI "extra=" hex
suffix on any item line appends raw bytes after the parsed item data.
This is used to preserve unknown item types and trailing data in
recognized items.
.SS Raw items
The
.BI "raw " hex
item type allows specifying item data as raw hexadecimal bytes,
bypassing all item-type-specific parsing.
.SH EXAMPLES
Dump a filesystem and reassemble it:
.PP
.nf
btrfs\-dump /dev/sda1 > fs.txt
btrfs\-assemble fs.txt fs.img
.fi
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR btrfs\-dump (1),
.BR btrfs (8),
.BR btrfs\-check (8)
.SH AUTHOR
Written by Mark Harmstone (\fBmark@harmstone.com\fR).
.SH WEB
https://github.com/maharmstone/btrfs-dump
